<span id="vii.iii.xi"></span>

<span id="vii.iii.xi-p1"></span> <span class="c1"><span
id="vii.iii.xi-p1.1"></span>Isaiah.</span>

<span id="vii.iii.xi-p2"></span>*Addressed to Paula and Eustochium,
about <span class="c17"><span id="vii.iii.xi-p2.1"></span>a.d.</span>
393. This Preface speaks of Isaiah as using the polished diction natural
to a man of rank and refinement, as an Evangelist more than a prophet,
and a poet rather than a prose writer. He then reiterates his defence of
his translation, saying that now, “The Jews can no longer scoff at our
Churches because of the falsity of our Scriptures.”*

